         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... the doing of (thi)ngs, [23a] the mind [is] the best, the mind comes first. ... [23b] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:carling2000"/><citedRange>403</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (Thereupon the suffering) follows him in the rebirths, [24a] the wheel of the deed, the cutting one rise(s up). [24b] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>277</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1967c"/><citedRange>165</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1979d"/><citedRange>163</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (But which is the de)ed which has been done and at the same time accumulated? [25a] It is this deed (which has been done) here due (to) the thought of ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:thomas1957"/><citedRange>277</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [25d] But which is the deed which has not been done and not accumulated? [26a] [It is this deed] which has been done unintention(ally). [26b] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [26d] || In [the tune] bahudantāk || Some beings having been hap(py here previously indeed) ... [1a] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... I will tell the way. Listen attentively! [1b] Here so(me beings ... they seize possession. [1c] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">… I will tell the … way, listen with one mind!  (cf 17)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>657</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (But) afterwards they are full of remorse. [1d] But these b(eings ... are born in a rich house) ... [2a] ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">they obtain the (pos)sessions and everything pleasant. [2b] ... [2c] ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... first happy, he feels suffering afterwards. [2d] But (which is the deed by which the beings after having been full of suffering first, afterwards become happy?) [3a] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>223</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they (begin) to speak loudly, but they hold on [to it = the gift] even under pain, [3b] while giving the gift ... </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:meunier2013"/><citedRange>178</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... they do (not) feel remorse, they become joyful. [3d] ... [4a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:hackstein1995"/><citedRange>136</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (when they beco)me great, by that time they grow in possession [and] they (become) rich. [4b] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (wenn) sie groß (werden), dann [wtl. zu der Zeit] nehmen sie an Besitz zu [und] (werden) reich.</seg><seg type="sec_transl" resp="TI">... (when) they (become) big, at that time they increase in possession [and] (become) rich.</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1974"/><citedRange>115</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... [4c] That is the deed through which beings (after having been) suffering first (become happy afterwards.) [4d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... (But what is the deed through which beings, if they are hap)py first indeed, become happy afterwards? [5a] Some bein(gs while giving a gift hold on to it being joyful, ... the giving of gift) ... [5b] ...</seg></seg><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(But what is the deed through which beings), if they are happy first, become happy afterwards [too]?  (cf 20)</seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:peyrot2013b"/><citedRange>327</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... and (afterw)ards they rejoice because of it [and] they do not become remorseful. [5c] (Stainle)ss [and] (pure [is] this gift, so pure to obtain a fruit [from it], and the beings rejoice) because of it.) [5d] ...</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b8"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... among humans they are reborn in a rich house (provided) with possession. [6a]</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="lingcomment">Note that om/postäṃ is three times written <hi>pos<hi rend="underline">t</hi>ä</hi> (a7, b1, b6). The anusvāra is missing, because of the <hi>ä</hi>-dots, since the anusvāra dot it is often missing when there are already two dots on the sign: nevertheless, the spelling with fremdzeichen ‹<hi rend="underline">ta</hi>› <hi>and</hi> <hi>ä</hi>-dots is strange.</note><note type="parallels"><ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas7d"/>; <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas7e"/>; Mahākarmavibhaṅga §§ 24-26 (<bibl><title corresp="ref:levi1932"/><citedRange>48, 121-122</citedRange></bibl>) (until a5); Mahākarmavibhaṅga §§ 33-34 (<bibl><title corresp="ref:levi1932"/><citedRange>65-66, 132-133</citedRange></bibl>) (from a5 onwards)</note><note type="philcomment">At the beginning, the text can be partly restored with he help of the parallel <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas7d"/>, and from line a5 on with the help of the parallel <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas7e"/>.</note><note type="philcomment">In the first part the meter has 4x12 (5/7) syllables, after stanza 26 in a5 the meter changes to 4 x 25 (5/5/8/7).</note></p>
         </div>
